problems.description: A boolean expression is an expression that is either true or false. The == operator can be used to compare two values. If they are the same, the result is True. If they are different, the result if False. Create a function call are_equal() that takes 2 numbers as parameters and returns True if they are equal and False if they are not.
problems.examples: For example, are_equal(5,5) will return true while are_equal(5,4) will return false.
problems.name: Boolean

problems.description: Another operator that can be used to compare two values is the > operator. This operator returns True if the value before it is greater than the value following it. For example: 5 >  4 = True. Create the function is_greater() that takes two numbers as parameters and returns True if the first number is greater than the second number.
problems.examples: For example, is_greater (5,4) will return true while is_greater (4,5) will return false.
problems.name: Greater Than

problems.description: Another operator that can be used to compare two values is the < operator. This operator returns True if the value before it is less than the value following it. For example: 4 <  5 = True. Create the function is_less() that takes two numbers as parameters and returns True if the first number is less than the second number.
problems.examples:
>>> is_less(4,5)
 True
>>> is_less(5,5)
 False
>>> is_less(5,4)
 False
problems.name: Less Than

problems.description: Another operator that can be used to compare two values is the >= operator. This operator returns True if the value before it is greater than or equal to the value following it. For example: 5 >= 5 = True. Create the function is_greater_or_equal() that takes two numbers as parameters and returns True if the first number is greater than or equal to the second number.
problems.solution:
def is_greater_or_equal(a,b):
  return a>=b
  return a>b
  return a>b
  return a<=b
  return a==b
problems.examples:
Example 1: is_greater_or_equal(5,4) will return true
Example 2: is_greater_or_equal(5,5) will return true
Example 3: is_greater_or_equal(4, 5) will return false
problems.name: Greater Than or Equal

problems.description: Another operator that can be used to compare two values is the <= operator. This operator returns True if the value before it is less than or equal to the value following it. For example: 5 <= 5 = True. Create the function is_less_or_equal() that takes two numbers as parameters and returns True if the first number is less than or equal to the second number.
problems.solution:
def is_less_or_equal(x,y):
  return x<=y
  return x>=y
  return x>y
  return x < y < 100
  return x==y
problems.examples:
Example 1: is_less_or_equal(4,5) will return true
Example 2: is_less_or_equal(5,5) will return true
Example 3: is_less_or_equal(5, 4) will return false
problems.name: Less Than or Equal

problems.description: Another operator that can be used to compare two values is the != operator. This operator returns True if the value before it is not equal to the value following it. For example: 5 != 4 = True. Create the function is_not_equal() that takes two numbers as parameters and returns True if the first number does not equal the second number.
problems.examples:
Example 1:  is_not_equal(4,5) will return true
Example 2: is_not_equal(5,5) will return false
Example 3: is_not_equal(5, 4) will return true
problems.name: Not Equal

problems.description: There are three logical operators: and, or, and not. These logical operators enable you to combine boolean statements (the ones that are True or False). Create the function in_range() that takes a single number as a parameter and returns if the number is greater than 0 and less than 5.
problems.solution:
def in_range(a):
  return a>0 and a<5
  return a>0 
  return a<5
  return a>0 or a<5
  return True
problems.examples:
For example: x > 0 and x < 5 = True only if x is between 0 and 5

Example 1: in_range(0) will return false
Example 2: in_range(3) will return true
Example 3: in_range(5) will return false
problems.name: And

problems.description: There are three logical operators: and, or, and not. These logical operators enable you to combine boolean statements (the ones that are True or False). For example: x > 5 or x < 0 = True only if x is greater than 5 or x is less than 0. Create the function in_range() that takes a single number as a parameter and returns True if the number is greater than 5 or less than 0.
problems.solution:
def in_range(a):
  return a>5 or a<0
  return a>5 and a<0
  return a>5 
  return a<0
  return a<5 or a>0
problems.examples:
For example: x > 5 or x < 0 = True only if x is greater than 5 or x is less than 0.

Example 1: in_range(0) will return false
Example 2: in_range(3) will return false
Example 3:  in_range(5) will return false
Example 4: in_range(-1) will return true
Example 5: in_range(6) will return true
problems.name: Or

problems.description: There are three logical operators: and, or, and not. These logical operators enable you to combine boolean statements. For example: x > 2 not x > 5 = True only if x is greater than 2 and not greater than 5. Create the function in_range() that takes a single number as a parameter and returns True if the number is greater than 2 and not greater than 5.
problems.solution:
def in_range(a):
  return a>2 and not a>5
  return a>2 and a>5
  return a<5 and a<2 
  return a<5
  return a<5 and not a>2
problems.examples:
>>> in_range(0)
 False
>>> in_range(3)
 True
>>> in_range(5)
 True
>>> in_range(6)
 False
problems.name: Not

problems.description: Sometimes, rather than return the result of a boolean expression you will want to do something different based on the evaluation of an expression. The if statement enables you to perform an operation depending on the result of some expression. Create the function is_positive() that takes a number as a parameter and returns the string 'Yes' if it is positive and 'No' if it is not.
problems.examples:
For example, if x > 0: return 'Yes'. 

Example 1: is_positive(0) will return yes
Example 2: is_positive(1) will return yes
Example 3:  is_positive(-1) will return no
problems.name: Conditional Execution

problems.description: In addition to the if statement, you can use the else statement which enables you to specify operations that will be performed when the if statement condition is not true. Create the function is_positive() that takes a number as a parameter and returns the string 'Yes' if it is positive and 'No' if it is not.
problems.examples:
For example, if x > 0: return 'Yes' else: return False.

Example 1: is_positive(0) will return yes
Example 2: is_positive(1) will return yes
Example 3: is_positive(-1) will return no
problems.name: Alternative Execution

problems.description: Using the if and else statement, create the function is_even() that takes a number as a parameter and returns the string 'Yes' if it is even and 'No' if it is not.
problems.examples:
For example, if you put an even number into the parameter of the function is_even(), you will get a true result

For example, is_even(0) will return yes while is_even(1) will return no
problems.name: Is Even

problems.description: In addition to the if  and else statement, you can use the elif (else if) statement to check for additional conditions before the else condition is executed. Create the function is_positive() that takes a number as a parameter and returns the string 'Yes' if it is positive and 'No' if it is not. However, if the parameter is 0, return 'Zero'.
problems.examples: For example, if you put a number that is bigger than zero into the parameter for the function is_positive(), you get a yes result while anything that is less than zero will get a no result. If the number is zero, is_positive(0) will return a zero result.
problems.name: Chained Conditionals
